<div id="review_1234239304" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1234239304" />
    <a title="Connie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17366942-connie"><img alt="Connie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578869721p2/17366942.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1234239304?book_show_action=true">Mar 22, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Connie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Connie" href="/user/show/17366942-connie">Connie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1234239304" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14135367946266975232"><br/> &quot;Deception on Sable Hill&quot; is the second of the Chicago World&apos;s Fair mysteries. Taking place in 1893, it highlights some of the changes brought about in Chicago by the influx of people who arrived in droves to view the spectacle that was the World&apos;s Fair.<br/>The time period is also significant as it seemed to whisper that the highly regimented social classes may have been coming unraveled. Children who had been brought up in the stricter times of their parents were questioning some of the restrictiv</span>
  <span id="freeText14135367946266975232" style="display:none"><br /> "Deception on Sable Hill" is the second of the Chicago World's Fair mysteries. Taking place in 1893, it highlights some of the changes brought about in Chicago by the influx of people who arrived in droves to view the spectacle that was the World's Fair.<br />The time period is also significant as it seemed to whisper that the highly regimented social classes may have been coming unraveled. Children who had been brought up in the stricter times of their parents were questioning some of the restrictive rules of the upper classes. And people who had been from solidly middle to lower working class were yearning for more opportunities for themselves and their children.<br />Shelley Gray does such a wonderful job weaving her story around the time period. Her characters are believable. I appreciated the friendship she created between Sean Ryan, a lower middle-class Irish cop and an upper class Owen Howard. It's interesting right from the beginning, as Ryan is Howard's superior. The men share another bond in that neither of their families is exactly pleased that being a policeman is their desired profession.<br />I enjoyed the story. It's a "clean read" with reality, romance, and suspense woven in. I look forward to the next installment of this series. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14135367946266975232" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


